High-level architecture: the frontend talks to FastAPI, FastAPI coordinates governance and execution, and long-running or unsafe work moves into workers and sandboxes.
How to Run It Locally
Before going into the architecture, here is the practical part.
The easiest way to run Mini Foundry is with Docker Compose. From the project root:
cp .env.example .env
docker compose up -d --buildThat starts the full local stack:

• PostgreSQL;

• Redis;

• MinIO;

• the FastAPI backend;

• the Celery worker;

• Celery beat;

• the Next.js frontend;

• Trino;

• the sandbox image build;

• database migrations.
After the containers are up, open:
http://localhost:3000The default local login is:
Email: admin@mini.local
Password: adminThe backend API docs are available at:
http://localhost:8000/docsThere is also a system health endpoint:
http://localhost:8000/api/v1/system/healthIf you want to enable the optional local AI provider, start the Ollama profile:
docker compose --profile ai up -d ollama ollama-initFor local development without running the backend and frontend only through Docker, the flow is:
cd backend
python -m venv .venv
source .venv/bin/activate
pip install --upgrade pip
pip install -r requirements.txt
alembic upgrade head
uvicorn app.main:app --reloadThen in another terminal:
cd frontend
cp .env.local.example .env.local
pnpm install
pnpm devThe normal smoke test is:

• Open http://localhost:3000.

• Log in as admin@mini.local / admin.

• Upload a CSV from the connectors page.

• Open the dataset in the catalog.

• Preview rows and columns.

• Use the SQL workspace to generate or run a query.

• Create an ontology object type from the dataset.

• Build an object set or pipeline.

• Check the audit page to see the recorded events.
That gives you the full platform loop: connect data, catalog it, govern it, query it, model it, build on it, and audit what happened.
Why I Started Building It
Most data stacks are powerful, but they often feel fragmented.
A team might use one tool for ingestion, another for transformations, another for dashboards, another for notebooks, another for permissions, another for AI, and another for business workflows. Each tool can be good on its own. The problem is what happens between them.
Permissions drift. Data gets copied. Lineage becomes incomplete. AI features are added on top without respecting governance. Business users see dashboards but not the underlying operational objects. Engineers understand pipelines, analysts understand SQL, operators understand workflows, and everyone is working in a slightly different model of reality.
The Foundry-style idea is different. It treats data as a governed operating layer, not just tables in a warehouse.
In that model:

• a dataset is not only a table;

• a dashboard is not only a chart;

• an object is not only a row;

• an action is not only an API call;

• AI is not an unrestricted shortcut around permission checks.
Everything lives inside a shared platform model.
That is what I wanted to explore with Mini Foundry.
The Product Shape
Mini Foundry currently covers most of the major platform areas at MVP level.
It has connectors for CSV, Parquet, Postgres, and REST APIs. It has a data catalog with profiling, preview, branching, quality, and lineage concepts. It has governed SQL with validation, row policies, column masking, policy-aware caching, and audit logging.
It also has visual pipelines, dashboards, notebooks, a code repository area, ML model pages, time-series support, an ontology system, object explorer, object sets, functions on objects, actions, writeback, applications, AI assistants, admin pages, jobs, schedules, approvals, exports, notifications, and operations views.
That is a lot of surface area. The point was not to make every feature complete on day one. The point was to prove that all these features could share the same foundation.
In the codebase, that foundation is the platform kernel.
The Runtime Architecture
The local development environment runs through Docker Compose.
The main services are:

• postgres, the main database;

• redis, used for cache and queue state;

• minio, used as S3-compatible storage;

• migrate, which runs Alembic migrations;

• backend, the FastAPI service on port 8000;

• worker, the Celery worker;

• beat, the Celery scheduler;

• frontend, the Next.js app on port 3000;

• trino, an optional SQL engine;

• ollama, an optional local AI provider;

• sandbox-image, the image used to run user Python safely.
The request path looks like this:
Browser
-> Next.js frontend
-> FastAPI /api/v1
-> PostgreSQL / Redis / MinIO / Celery
-> optional worker or sandbox execution
-> audit log
-> governed responseThe backend registers all feature routers under /api/v1. On startup it performs a few important tasks:

• checks production hardening settings;

• creates the first admin user if needed;

• optionally seeds demo data;

• syncs existing domain objects into the shared resources table;

• loads user workflow definitions;

• exposes health endpoints.
That startup sync is important. The platform has many domain objects: datasets, pipelines, dashboards, apps, models, and so on. The resource sync makes sure those objects can be governed through the shared platform model.
The Principle Behind the Backend
The most important principle in the backend is simple:
Sensitive operations should pass through backend enforcement, not rely on the frontend being careful.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

That sounds obvious, but it is easy to violate in a large app.
For example, if a SQL editor checks permissions but a dashboard preview does not, the dashboard becomes a bypass. If the object explorer applies row policies but notebook execution does not, notebooks become a bypass. If AI can send data to a cloud provider without checking dataset policy, AI becomes a bypass.
So the intended execution flow is:
resolve resource
-> resolve branch or version context
-> check capability
-> apply markings
-> apply row policies
-> apply column masks
-> validate query or action
-> execute through approved path
-> record lineage/version/audit
-> return resultThe codebase is not perfect yet, but this is the architecture it is moving toward. The architecture checklist in the repo is intentionally honest about what is done and what remains.
The Platform Kernel
The platform kernel lives mainly in backend/app/platform.
It introduces shared concepts that other features use:

• projects;

• resources;

• resource versions;

• resource ACLs;

• markings;

• branches;

• schema versions;

• dataset versions;

• pipeline versions;

• build runs;

• build inputs and outputs;

• access requests;

• approval requests;

• export requests.
The key model is Resource.
A resource has a type, object ID, name, parent resource, project, owner, lifecycle state, metadata, creation time, update time, and deletion time. This lets different feature objects participate in the same governance model.
A dataset can be a resource. A pipeline can be a resource. A dashboard can be a resource. A model can be a resource. An app can be a resource.
That matters because the platform can ask a consistent question:
Does this user have this capability on this resource?
The answer comes from ResourceACL.
Capabilities are intentionally more granular than broad roles. Examples include:

• view_metadata;

• view_data;

• use_in_sql;

• use_in_python;

• use_with_ai;

• export;

• edit;

• manage;

• run;

• publish;

• writeback.
This is closer to how a serious data platform needs to work. A user might be allowed to see that a dataset exists, but not preview rows. They might be allowed to use a dataset in SQL, but not export it. They might be allowed to run a pipeline, but not edit it. They might be allowed to use a dataset with local AI, but not with a cloud AI provider.
Mini Foundry also separates ACLs from markings. Markings are classification-like labels that can apply to resources. They are useful for policy layers where normal permissions are not enough.
Data Ingestion
Data enters Mini Foundry through connectors.
Today the project supports:

• CSV upload;

• Parquet upload;

• Postgres connector;

• REST API connector;

• early stream source and subscription metadata.
The connector layer creates data sources, datasets, dataset columns, jobs, versions, and lineage records. It also stores connection metadata carefully. Sensitive connector config fields are hidden in responses, and secret handling is separated into the permissions/secrets layer.
A simple CSV upload flow looks like this:
User uploads CSV
-> backend infers schema
-> staging table is created
-> rows are loaded
-> Dataset row is created
-> DatasetColumn rows are created
-> resource is registered
-> dataset version is recorded
-> audit/logging events are written
-> catalog can show preview/profileFor Postgres, the connector can discover schemas and preview tables. For REST APIs, configuration can describe pagination and authentication. For Parquet, storage can go through the object storage layer.
The important thing is that ingestion is not treated as just “put a table somewhere.” It creates governed platform objects that other systems can use.
The Catalog
The data catalog is the user-facing home for datasets.
It shows dataset metadata, columns, profiles, row preview, quality information, lineage, branches, and related resources. From the catalog, a dataset can flow into several other parts of the platform:

• governed SQL;

• dashboards;

• pipelines;

• notebooks;

• object types;

• object sets;

• AI-assisted workflows;

• exports;

• access requests.
This is one of the reasons a catalog is more than a data dictionary. In Mini Foundry, the catalog is where a dataset becomes a governed resource inside the platform.
The project also has dataset versions and schema versions. This is the beginning of reproducibility. Some paths already understand pinned versions, especially around DuckDB-style storage artifacts. Other paths still need stronger version pinning before I would call the platform production-safe.
That is one of the main roadmap items.
